---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';

const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
const baseNormalized = base.endsWith('/') ? base : `${base}/`;
const imgBase = `${baseNormalized}images/case-studies/ai-chat/`;
---

<Layout
	title="AI Chat: GitLab Duo & watsonx Code Assistant | Sam Reiss"
	description="Case study: designing AI chat systems for technical users across IBM watsonx Code Assistant and GitLab Duo Chat."
>
	<main>
		<p class="back-link"><a href={import.meta.env.BASE_URL}>Back to homepage</a></p>

		<article class="case-study case-study-rich" lang="en">
			<header class="case-study-header case-study-header-rich" id="case-study-top">
				<p class="section-kicker">Case Study</p>
				<div class="case-study-header-main">
					<h1>Designing AI Chat Systems for Technical Users</h1>
					<p class="case-subtitle">
						From leading the design of IBM watsonx Code Assistant to contributing to GitLab Duo
						Chat, this work explores how chat evolves from a conversational interface into a system
						for action.
					</p>
					<dl class="case-meta-row">
						<div class="case-meta-item">
							<dt>
								<a
									class="case-anchor-link case-anchor-link-meta"
									href="#ibm-watsonx-code-assistant"
									aria-label="Jump to IBM watsonx Code Assistant section"
								>
									IBM watsonx Code Assistant
									<span class="case-anchor-icon-wrap" aria-hidden="true">
										<svg class="case-anchor-icon" width="14" height="14" viewBox="0 0 16 16" focusable="false">
											<path
												fill="none"
												stroke="currentColor"
												stroke-width="1.5"
												stroke-linecap="round"
												stroke-linejoin="round"
												d="M3.5 6.5 8 11l4.5-4.5M8 11V2.5"></path>
										</svg>
									</span>
								</a>
							</dt>
							<dd>Lead Designer</dd>
						</div>
						<div class="case-meta-item">
							<dt>
								<a
									class="case-anchor-link case-anchor-link-meta"
									href="#gitlab-duo-chat"
									aria-label="Jump to GitLab Duo Chat section"
								>
									GitLab Duo Chat
									<span class="case-anchor-icon-wrap" aria-hidden="true">
										<svg class="case-anchor-icon" width="14" height="14" viewBox="0 0 16 16" focusable="false">
											<path
												fill="none"
												stroke="currentColor"
												stroke-width="1.5"
												stroke-linecap="round"
												stroke-linejoin="round"
												d="M3.5 6.5 8 11l4.5-4.5M8 11V2.5"></path>
										</svg>
									</span>
								</a>
							</dt>
							<dd>Supporting Designer, team of 3 senior designers</dd>
						</div>
						<div class="case-meta-item case-meta-item-wide">
							<dt>Focus</dt>
							<dd>AI chat, developer tools, IDE UX, agent workflows, feedback loops</dd>
						</div>
					</dl>
				</div>
			</header>

			<section class="case-section case-section-rich" aria-labelledby="overview-heading">
				<h2 id="overview-heading">Overview</h2>
				<div class="case-section-body">
					<p class="case-lede">
						I design interaction systems that help technical users understand, control, and
						trust AI-powered workflows.
					</p>
					<p>
						This case study compares two related efforts: IBM watsonx Code Assistant, an
						IDE-integrated coding assistant, and GitLab Duo Chat, a platform chat experience
						evolving toward agents, flows, sessions, and model choice. Together they sit under
						one throughline: designing AI chat systems for technical users across IDE-native and
						platform-native environments.
					</p>
					<p class="case-overview-themes">
						Across both, the work keeps returning to the same pressures: read the user's situation
						(files, surface, and session) before responding; shorten the distance between a clear
						answer and a useful next step; and keep interaction patterns legible inside the wider
						product so chat feels contiguous with everyday developer habits—not a parallel
						experience.
					</p>
				</div>
			</section>

			<section
				class="case-section case-section-rich case-section-product case-section-ibm"
				aria-labelledby="ibm-watsonx-code-assistant"
			>
				<h2 id="ibm-watsonx-code-assistant">
					<a
						class="case-anchor-link case-anchor-link-back"
						href="#case-study-top"
						aria-label="Back to top of case study"
					>
						IBM watsonx Code Assistant
						<span class="case-anchor-icon-wrap" aria-hidden="true">
							<svg class="case-anchor-icon" width="14" height="14" viewBox="0 0 16 16" focusable="false">
								<path
									fill="none"
									stroke="currentColor"
									stroke-width="1.5"
									stroke-linecap="round"
									stroke-linejoin="round"
									d="M3.5 9.5 8 5l4.5 4.5M8 5v8.5"></path>
							</svg>
						</span>
					</a>
				</h2>
				<div class="case-section-body case-section-body-ibm-lead">
					<p class="case-role-lede" role="note">
						I led the integrated chat experience, partnered with engineering and Carbon, delivered the
						high-fidelity UI, and owned the end-to-end design direction for this workstream.
					</p>
				</div>

				<div
					class="case-section-body case-section-body-ibm-rest case-section-body-ibm-before-carousel case-ibm-compact-blocks"
				>
					<div class="case-ibm-lede-meta-row">
						<div class="case-ibm-mini-col">
							<h3 class="case-inline-heading">Problem</h3>
							<p>
								IBM had existing AI chat explorations, but they were designed for browser-based IBM
								software, not the constraints of an IDE plugin.
							</p>
						</div>
						<div class="case-ibm-mini-col">
							<h3 class="case-inline-heading">My role</h3>
							<p>
								I led a team of two UX designers, delivered the high-fidelity design work, partnered
								with engineering, and consulted with the Carbon Design System team.
							</p>
						</div>
						<div class="case-ibm-mini-col">
							<h3 class="case-inline-heading">Design challenge</h3>
							<p>
								Adapt Carbon AI chat patterns into a constrained IDE environment while preserving
								brand consistency and continuity with how developers already work.
							</p>
						</div>
					</div>
				</div>

				<div
					class="case-carousel case-figure case-figure-editorial case-figure-ibm-carousel"
					data-case-carousel
					role="region"
					aria-roledescription="carousel"
					aria-label="watsonx Code Assistant shipped UI, system views, and IDE integration"
					tabindex="0"
				>
						<div class="case-carousel-viewport">
							<div class="case-carousel-track" data-carousel-track>
								<figure class="case-carousel-slide is-active" data-carousel-slide aria-hidden="false">
									<div class="case-editorial-media">
										<img
											src={`${imgBase}watsonx-final-chat-ui.png`}
											alt="Shipped watsonx Code Assistant chat interface in the IDE with responses and controls."
											loading="eager"
											width="1200"
											height="675"
										/>
									</div>
									<figcaption class="case-carousel-figcaption">
										The shipped chat UI balanced Carbon alignment with IDE density and developer
										expectations.
									</figcaption>
								</figure>
								<figure class="case-carousel-slide" data-carousel-slide aria-hidden="true">
									<div class="case-editorial-media">
										<img
											src={`${imgBase}watsonx-files-and-model-transparency.png`}
											alt="UI showing file references, model selection, and response metadata in chat."
											loading="lazy"
											width="1200"
											height="675"
										/>
									</div>
									<figcaption class="case-carousel-figcaption">
										File touches and model visibility made outputs easier to audit and trust.
									</figcaption>
								</figure>
								<figure class="case-carousel-slide" data-carousel-slide aria-hidden="true">
									<div class="case-editorial-media">
										<img
											src={`${imgBase}watsonx-session-management.png`}
											alt="Session list and detail views for chat threads in the assistant."
											loading="lazy"
											width="1200"
											height="675"
										/>
									</div>
									<figcaption class="case-carousel-figcaption">
										Sessions behaved like trackable units of work, not a flat transcript.
									</figcaption>
								</figure>
								<figure class="case-carousel-slide" data-carousel-slide aria-hidden="true">
									<div class="case-editorial-media">
										<img
											src={`${imgBase}watsonx-code-generation-context.png`}
											alt="Generated code snippet offered inline next to the conversation in the IDE."
											loading="lazy"
											width="1200"
											height="675"
										/>
									</div>
									<figcaption class="case-carousel-figcaption">
										Generated code stayed in context so review, apply, and iterate stayed one gesture
										apart.
									</figcaption>
								</figure>
								<figure class="case-carousel-slide" data-carousel-slide aria-hidden="true">
									<div class="case-editorial-media">
										<img
											src={`${imgBase}watsonx-ide-integration.png`}
											alt="watsonx Code Assistant chat panel docked in the IDE beside editor and file tree."
											loading="lazy"
											width="1995"
											height="1228"
										/>
									</div>
									<figcaption class="case-carousel-figcaption">
										IDE-native placement kept chat adjacent to the code users were already editing.
									</figcaption>
								</figure>
							</div>
						</div>
						<div class="case-carousel-toolbar">
							<p class="case-carousel-index" aria-live="polite" aria-atomic="true">
								<span class="case-carousel-index-current" data-carousel-index-current>01</span>
								<span class="case-carousel-index-sep" aria-hidden="true"> — </span>
								<span class="case-carousel-index-total" data-carousel-index-total>05</span>
							</p>
							<div class="case-carousel-arrows">
								<button
									type="button"
									class="case-carousel-btn case-carousel-btn-minimal"
									data-carousel-prev
									aria-label="Previous image"
								>
									<svg width="22" height="22" viewBox="0 0 16 16" aria-hidden="true" focusable="false">
										<path
											fill="none"
											stroke="currentColor"
											stroke-width="1"
											stroke-linecap="round"
											stroke-linejoin="round"
											d="M10 3 5 8l5 5"></path>
									</svg>
								</button>
								<button
									type="button"
									class="case-carousel-btn case-carousel-btn-minimal"
									data-carousel-next
									aria-label="Next image"
								>
									<svg width="22" height="22" viewBox="0 0 16 16" aria-hidden="true" focusable="false">
										<path
											fill="none"
											stroke="currentColor"
											stroke-width="1"
											stroke-linecap="round"
											stroke-linejoin="round"
											d="M6 3l5 5-5 5"></path>
									</svg>
								</button>
							</div>
						</div>
				</div>

				<div
					class="case-section-body case-section-body-ibm-rest case-section-body-ibm-after-carousel case-ibm-compact-blocks"
				>
					<div class="case-ibm-post-carousel">
						<div class="case-ibm-decisions-section">
							<h3 class="case-inline-heading">Key design decisions</h3>
							<ol class="case-numbered case-ibm-decisions-cols">
								<li>
									Adapt browser-based AI chat patterns to fit the constraints and ergonomics of an
									IDE plugin.
								</li>
								<li>
									Design for in-context work, ensuring outputs like code and explanations integrate
									directly into the developer's flow.
								</li>
								<li>
									Treat chat as a persistent workspace, with session management and feedback
									supporting iteration over time.
								</li>
							</ol>
						</div>
						<div class="case-ibm-outcome-section">
							<h3 class="case-inline-heading">Outcome</h3>
							<p>
								After launch, the updated chat UI saw an 87% increase in WCA downloads and enabled
								inline feedback collection for the LLM team. Some of the work also informed Carbon
								AI Chat components.
							</p>
						</div>
					</div>
				</div>
			</section>

			<section
				class="case-section case-section-rich case-section-product case-section-gitlab"
				aria-labelledby="gitlab-duo-chat"
			>
				<h2 id="gitlab-duo-chat">
					<a
						class="case-anchor-link case-anchor-link-back"
						href="#case-study-top"
						aria-label="Back to top of case study"
					>
						GitLab Duo Chat
						<span class="case-anchor-icon-wrap" aria-hidden="true">
							<svg class="case-anchor-icon" width="14" height="14" viewBox="0 0 16 16" focusable="false">
								<path
									fill="none"
									stroke="currentColor"
									stroke-width="1.5"
									stroke-linecap="round"
									stroke-linejoin="round"
									d="M3.5 9.5 8 5l4.5 4.5M8 5v8.5"></path>
							</svg>
						</span>
					</a>
				</h2>

				<div class="case-section-body case-section-body-gitlab-lead case-gitlab-span-c2">
					<p class="case-role-lede" role="note">
						I contributed as one of three senior designers shaping Duo Chat, focusing on interaction
						patterns, workflow concepts, and system coherence across the experience.
					</p>
				</div>

				<div
					class="case-section-body case-section-body-gitlab-rest case-gitlab-triad case-ibm-compact-blocks case-gitlab-span-c2"
				>
					<div class="case-ibm-lede-meta-row">
						<div class="case-ibm-mini-col">
							<h3 class="case-inline-heading">Problem</h3>
							<p>
								Early chat patterns treated interactions as linear conversation. This broke down as
								capabilities expanded into multi-step workflows, agent execution, and persistent
								context.
							</p>
						</div>
						<div class="case-ibm-mini-col">
							<h3 class="case-inline-heading">My role</h3>
							<p>
								Contributed to core interaction patterns across chat, sessions, and agent flows.
								Partnered closely with product and engineering to define end-to-end UX behavior.
								Helped align emerging patterns into a cohesive system across surfaces.
							</p>
						</div>
						<div class="case-ibm-mini-col">
							<h3 class="case-inline-heading">Design challenge</h3>
							<p>
								How might chat evolve from a simple prompt-response interface into a system that
								supports ongoing, stateful work, multiple execution paths, and transparency without
								adding cognitive overhead?
							</p>
						</div>
					</div>
				</div>

				<figure class="case-figure case-figure-editorial case-gitlab-hero case-gitlab-span-full">
					<div class="case-editorial-media">
						<img
							src={`${imgBase}gitlab-duo-session-details.png`}
							alt="GitLab Duo Chat session list and detail view showing AI work as trackable sessions."
							loading="eager"
							width="1200"
							height="675"
						/>
					</div>
					<figcaption>Sessions and detail views framed Duo as a place to follow AI-driven work, not only a transcript.</figcaption>
				</figure>

				<div class="case-section-body case-gitlab-kd-copy case-ibm-compact-blocks case-gitlab-span-c2">
					<h3 class="case-inline-heading">Structuring chat as ongoing work</h3>
					<p>
						Chat evolved from linear conversation into structured, persistent work. Sessions became
						trackable units with clear state, recency, and re-entry points.
					</p>
				</div>

				<div
					class="case-carousel case-figure case-figure-editorial case-figure-gitlab-carousel case-gitlab-span-full"
					data-case-carousel
					role="region"
					aria-roledescription="carousel"
					aria-label="GitLab Duo Chat sessions and agent selection"
					tabindex="0"
				>
					<div class="case-carousel-viewport">
						<div class="case-carousel-track" data-carousel-track>
							<figure class="case-carousel-slide is-active" data-carousel-slide aria-hidden="false">
								<div class="case-editorial-media">
									<img
										src={`${imgBase}gitlab-duo-session-details.png`}
										alt="Session list and session detail in Duo Chat."
										loading="lazy"
										width="1200"
										height="675"
									/>
								</div>
								<figcaption class="case-carousel-figcaption">
									Sessions read as trackable units of work with status, recency, and clear paths back in.
								</figcaption>
							</figure>
							<figure class="case-carousel-slide" data-carousel-slide aria-hidden="true">
								<div class="case-editorial-media">
									<img
										src={`${imgBase}gitlab-duo-agent-switching.png`}
										alt="Agent switching UI in Duo Chat."
										loading="lazy"
										width="1200"
										height="675"
									/>
								</div>
								<figcaption class="case-carousel-figcaption">
									Agents stayed discoverable from the chat surface rather than buried in settings.
								</figcaption>
							</figure>
						</div>
					</div>
					<div class="case-carousel-toolbar">
						<p class="case-carousel-index" aria-live="polite" aria-atomic="true">
							<span class="case-carousel-index-current" data-carousel-index-current>01</span>
							<span class="case-carousel-index-sep" aria-hidden="true"> — </span>
							<span class="case-carousel-index-total" data-carousel-index-total>02</span>
						</p>
						<div class="case-carousel-arrows">
							<button
								type="button"
								class="case-carousel-btn case-carousel-btn-minimal"
								data-carousel-prev
								aria-label="Previous image"
							>
								<svg width="22" height="22" viewBox="0 0 16 16" aria-hidden="true" focusable="false">
									<path
										fill="none"
										stroke="currentColor"
										stroke-width="1"
										stroke-linecap="round"
										stroke-linejoin="round"
										d="M10 3 5 8l5 5"></path>
								</svg>
							</button>
							<button
								type="button"
								class="case-carousel-btn case-carousel-btn-minimal"
								data-carousel-next
								aria-label="Next image"
							>
								<svg width="22" height="22" viewBox="0 0 16 16" aria-hidden="true" focusable="false">
									<path
										fill="none"
										stroke="currentColor"
										stroke-width="1"
										stroke-linecap="round"
										stroke-linejoin="round"
										d="M6 3l5 5-5 5"></path>
								</svg>
							</button>
						</div>
					</div>
				</div>

				<div class="case-section-body case-gitlab-kd-copy case-ibm-compact-blocks case-gitlab-span-c2">
					<h3 class="case-inline-heading">Bridging prompts to execution</h3>
					<p>
						We introduced clearer pathways from intent to action, allowing users to move from natural
						language into structured workflows without breaking flow.
					</p>
				</div>

				<div
					class="case-carousel case-figure case-figure-editorial case-figure-gitlab-carousel case-gitlab-span-full"
					data-case-carousel
					role="region"
					aria-roledescription="carousel"
					aria-label="GitLab Duo Chat slash commands and suggestions"
					tabindex="0"
				>
					<div class="case-carousel-viewport">
						<div class="case-carousel-track" data-carousel-track>
							<figure class="case-carousel-slide is-active" data-carousel-slide aria-hidden="false">
								<div class="case-editorial-media">
									<img
										src={`${imgBase}gitlab-duo-slash-command-invoke.png`}
										alt="Slash command invoked in Duo Chat composer."
										loading="lazy"
										width="1200"
										height="675"
									/>
								</div>
								<figcaption class="case-carousel-figcaption">
									Slash commands helped move from a prompt into a structured flow with explicit intent.
								</figcaption>
							</figure>
							<figure class="case-carousel-slide" data-carousel-slide aria-hidden="true">
								<div class="case-editorial-media">
									<img
										src={`${imgBase}gitlab-duo-suggestions-panel.png`}
										alt="Contextual suggestions panel in Duo Chat."
										loading="lazy"
										width="1200"
										height="675"
									/>
								</div>
								<figcaption class="case-carousel-figcaption">
									Suggestions offered relevant starting points without derailing the composer.
								</figcaption>
							</figure>
						</div>
					</div>
					<div class="case-carousel-toolbar">
						<p class="case-carousel-index" aria-live="polite" aria-atomic="true">
							<span class="case-carousel-index-current" data-carousel-index-current>01</span>
							<span class="case-carousel-index-sep" aria-hidden="true"> — </span>
							<span class="case-carousel-index-total" data-carousel-index-total>02</span>
						</p>
						<div class="case-carousel-arrows">
							<button
								type="button"
								class="case-carousel-btn case-carousel-btn-minimal"
								data-carousel-prev
								aria-label="Previous image"
							>
								<svg width="22" height="22" viewBox="0 0 16 16" aria-hidden="true" focusable="false">
									<path
										fill="none"
										stroke="currentColor"
										stroke-width="1"
										stroke-linecap="round"
										stroke-linejoin="round"
										d="M10 3 5 8l5 5"></path>
								</svg>
							</button>
							<button
								type="button"
								class="case-carousel-btn case-carousel-btn-minimal"
								data-carousel-next
								aria-label="Next image"
							>
								<svg width="22" height="22" viewBox="0 0 16 16" aria-hidden="true" focusable="false">
									<path
										fill="none"
										stroke="currentColor"
										stroke-width="1"
										stroke-linecap="round"
										stroke-linejoin="round"
										d="M6 3l5 5-5 5"></path>
								</svg>
							</button>
						</div>
					</div>
				</div>

				<div class="case-section-body case-gitlab-kd-copy case-ibm-compact-blocks case-gitlab-span-c2">
					<h3 class="case-inline-heading">Making system behavior legible</h3>
					<p>
						As capabilities expanded, visibility became critical. Model choice, modes, and feedback were
						surfaced directly in the interface to build trust and support iteration.
					</p>
				</div>

				<div
					class="case-carousel case-figure case-figure-editorial case-figure-gitlab-carousel case-gitlab-span-full"
					data-case-carousel
					role="region"
					aria-roledescription="carousel"
					aria-label="GitLab Duo Chat models, modes, and feedback"
					tabindex="0"
				>
					<div class="case-carousel-viewport">
						<div class="case-carousel-track" data-carousel-track>
							<figure class="case-carousel-slide is-active" data-carousel-slide aria-hidden="false">
								<div class="case-editorial-media">
									<img
										src={`${imgBase}gitlab-duo-model-switcher.png`}
										alt="Model switcher in Duo Chat."
										loading="lazy"
										width="1200"
										height="675"
									/>
								</div>
								<figcaption class="case-carousel-figcaption">
									Model choice stayed visible without crowding the composer.
								</figcaption>
							</figure>
